In [28]:
# Set the size of the figure to be displayed
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 8))

# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('Average Daily Rate in City and Resort Hotel', fontsize=30)

# Plot the ADR data for the resort hotel, with the index (i.e. the x-axis) representing the date
# The label parameter specifies the label to be used for this line in the legend
plt.plot(resort_hotel.index, resort_hotel['adr'], label='Resort Hotel')

# Plot the ADR data for the city hotel, with the index (i.e. the x-axis) representing the date
# The label parameter specifies the label to be used for this line in the legend
plt.plot(city_hotel.index, city_hotel['adr'], label='City Hotel')

# Add a legend to the plot, with a font size of 20
plt.legend(fontsize=20)

# Display the plot
plt.show()
In [29]:
# Create a new column in the DataFrame to extract the month from the reservation_status_date column
df['month'] = df['reservation_status_date'].dt.month

# Set the size of the figure to be displayed
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))

# Create a countplot using seaborn, with the month on the x-axis, and the count of reservations on the y-axis, grouped by cancellation status
# The hue parameter specifies the column to use for grouping the data, in this case the 'is_canceled' column
# The palette parameter specifies the color scheme to use for the bars
ax1 = sns.countplot(x='month', hue='is_canceled', data=df, palette='bright')

# Get the legend labels and handles from the seaborn countplot
# The first variable returned is a list of the legend labels
# The second variable is not needed here, so we use the underscore (_) to indicate that we are ignoring it
legend_labels, _ = ax1.get_legend_handles_labels()

# Add the legend to the plot, using the bbox_to_anchor parameter to specify the position of the legend outside the plot area
# In this case, the legend is positioned in the upper right corner of the plot
ax1.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))

# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('Reservation status per month', size=20)

# Label the x-axis
plt.xlabel('month')

# Label the y-axis
plt.ylabel('number of reservations')

# Add a legend to the plot, with labels for the 'not canceled' and 'canceled' groups
plt.legend(['not canceled', 'canceled'])

# Display the plot
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
plt.title('ADR per month', fontsize=30)

# Group data by month and sum ADR for canceled bookings only
df_cancelled = df[df['is_canceled'] == 1].groupby('month')[['adr']].sum().reset_index()

# Plot bar chart
sns.barplot(x='month', y='adr', data=df_cancelled)

# Add legend with labels
plt.legend(['ADR'], fontsize=20)

plt.show()
